WEBVTT

1
00:00:51.533 --> 00:00:53.834
We're going to have
to tell our Hyacinth.

2
00:00:53.834 --> 00:00:55.800
Oh. god.
Not tonight.

3
00:00:55.800 --> 00:00:59.600
Tomorrow morning.
I couldn't face Hyacinth.
Not tonight.

4
00:00:59.600 --> 00:01:01.600
<i>Now. ladies.

5
00:01:10.667 --> 00:01:13.633
- You're new.
- Only around here. lady.

6
00:01:13.633 --> 00:01:16.667
- Have you nothing
for this address?
- Sorry.

7
00:01:16.667 --> 00:01:20.434
I'd be greatly obliged
if you'd make quite sure.

8
00:01:23.667 --> 00:01:27.567
There's usually something
for a Mrs. Richard bouquet.

9
00:01:27.567 --> 00:01:31.900
- How do you
spell "bouquet"?
- B-u-c-k-e-t.

10
00:01:31.900 --> 00:01:33.834
What?

11
00:01:33.834 --> 00:01:39.267
B-u-c-k-e-t.

12
00:01:39.267 --> 00:01:40.967
Oh. bucket.

13
00:01:40.967 --> 00:01:44.001
It's "bouquet."

14
00:01:44.001 --> 00:01:47.567
I'm sorry lady.
There's nothing here
for "bouquet."

15
00:01:47.567 --> 00:01:50.067
Nothing?
For this address?

16
00:01:50.067 --> 00:01:52.434
Yet you have something
for next door?

17
00:01:52.434 --> 00:01:54.267
I find that very strange.

18
00:01:54.267 --> 00:01:55.600
I can't help that.
lady.

19
00:01:55.600 --> 00:01:57.834
But people will
tell you.

20
00:01:57.834 --> 00:02:01.201
it's common knowledge
I receive more mail
than these next door.

21
00:02:04.134 --> 00:02:06.767
There must be a card
from my sister
in tenerife.

22
00:02:06.767 --> 00:02:09.834
She's back home.
but we're still waiting
for the card.

23
00:02:11.434 --> 00:02:13.633
Anything wrong.
Hyacinth?

24
00:02:13.633 --> 00:02:16.600
He's mislaid my letters
at the sorting office.

25
00:02:16.600 --> 00:02:19.600
This would never have happened
with my former postman.

26
00:02:22.167 --> 00:02:24.034
You will remember.
Elizabeth.

27
00:02:24.034 --> 00:02:26.967
that you're invited this evening
to my candlelight supper?

28
00:02:26.967 --> 00:02:31.067
It's engraved on
my mind. Hyacinth.

29
00:02:31.067 --> 00:02:33.368
Telephone. dear.
You're wanted on
the phone.

30
00:02:33.368 --> 00:02:35.167
I think it's urgent.

31
00:02:35.167 --> 00:02:38.500
I'm not offering an opinion.
That's what she said. urgent.

32
00:02:38.500 --> 00:02:42.134
Please don't shout
in that excitable manner
outdoors. Richard.

33
00:02:42.134 --> 00:02:44.834
I don't like you getting
excited outdoors.

34
00:02:49.667 --> 00:02:51.633
Morning. major.

35
00:02:51.633 --> 00:02:53.434
By god. woman.

36
00:02:53.434 --> 00:02:55.867
You could drive a man mad
looking so attractive

37
00:02:55.867 --> 00:02:57.867
so early in the day.

38
00:03:00.101 --> 00:03:02.134
Oh. major.

39
00:03:02.134 --> 00:03:05.667
You'll not forget
my little candlelight
supper this evening?

40
00:03:05.667 --> 00:03:08.101
19:30 hours.

41
00:03:08.101 --> 00:03:10.867
I'll be there.
you minx.

42
00:03:10.867 --> 00:03:14.101
You can always tell
breeding.

43
00:03:17.633 --> 00:03:20.567
The phone. Hyacinth.
It think it's urgent.

44
00:03:20.567 --> 00:03:22.934
It's about your father.

45
00:03:26.633 --> 00:03:28.800
We're going to have
to emulsion this ceiling.

46
00:03:28.800 --> 00:03:30.533
We've just done it.

47
00:03:30.533 --> 00:03:32.934
It's not a fit ceiling
to bring a major under.

48
00:03:32.934 --> 00:03:35.533
It's your sister. Daisy.

49
00:03:35.533 --> 00:03:37.468
She's not coming.
is she?

50
00:03:37.468 --> 00:03:39.468
Not in that awful coat.

51
00:03:39.468 --> 00:03:42.334
And he's not bringing her.
Not in that rust bucket
of a car.

52
00:03:42.334 --> 00:03:44.667
- I will not have them--
- I think it's urgent.

53
00:03:44.667 --> 00:03:47.500
It's so thoughtless
to look as poor
as they do.

54
00:03:48.667 --> 00:03:51.401
Daisy. how are you. dear?

55
00:03:51.401 --> 00:03:53.800
Daddy ill?
How ill?

56
00:03:53.800 --> 00:03:57.401
Is it of a severity
necessary to cancel
my candlelight supper?

57
00:03:59.401 --> 00:04:02.301
What was he doing
at his age on a bicycle?

58
00:04:03.934 --> 00:04:06.434
Oh my god.

59
00:04:06.434 --> 00:04:08.234
How much to drink?

60
00:04:09.700 --> 00:04:12.167
Yes. Hyacinth.

61
00:04:13.633 --> 00:04:15.334
What did she say?

62
00:04:15.334 --> 00:04:18.867
She says not to go
over to her place.
She's coming here.

63
00:04:18.867 --> 00:04:21.967
That's all we need.
a royal visit.

64
00:04:21.967 --> 00:04:25.800
I was hoping she'd go
straight to the hospital.

65
00:04:25.800 --> 00:04:28.834
They won't let anybody in
until visiting time.

66
00:04:28.834 --> 00:04:30.867
Don't you remember
when I was in

67
00:04:30.867 --> 00:04:33.633
having that breakdown
on account of Mr. Crabtree?

68
00:04:34.734 --> 00:04:38.034
What ever happened
to Mr. Crabtree?

69
00:04:38.034 --> 00:04:41.967
I swore i'd
never see him again.

70
00:04:41.967 --> 00:04:46.934
And for a while
I cut it back ruthlessly
to every other Tuesday.

71
00:04:46.934 --> 00:04:50.600
Does Boris know about
you still seeing
Mr. Crabtree?

72
00:04:50.600 --> 00:04:52.967
Of course he doesn't.
Do you think I'm stupid?

73
00:04:52.967 --> 00:04:56.600
I don't know
how you keep
the pace up. Rose.

74
00:04:56.600 --> 00:04:58.834
It's not easy.

75
00:04:58.834 --> 00:05:02.468
If you relax for a minute
they're going back
to their wives.

76
00:05:03.667 --> 00:05:06.434
I envy you. Daisy.

77
00:05:06.434 --> 00:05:08.067
Me?

78
00:05:08.067 --> 00:05:12.034
It must be wonderful
being married to a bum
like your onslow.

79
00:05:13.667 --> 00:05:16.334
So you can let
yourself go completely.

80
00:05:16.334 --> 00:05:19.468
I wouldn't say completely.

81
00:05:19.468 --> 00:05:21.468
Near enough.
completely.

82
00:05:22.834 --> 00:05:27.001
Get a shirt on. onslow.
Hyacinth's coming.

83
00:05:27.001 --> 00:05:28.800
How nice.

84
00:05:28.800 --> 00:05:32.834
She's going to want
to know exactly
what happened.

85
00:05:32.834 --> 00:05:35.134
You'll have to tell her.

86
00:05:35.134 --> 00:05:37.567
I don't see why
I should have
to tell her.

87
00:05:37.567 --> 00:05:40.734
You'll have
to tell her because...

88
00:05:40.734 --> 00:05:43.700
I'll be too busy
tidying up.

89
00:05:44.800 --> 00:05:47.001
I hate tidying up.

90
00:05:47.001 --> 00:05:49.401
I'm under the doctor
for being dizzy.

91
00:05:49.401 --> 00:05:52.267
I'm sure it's tidying up.

92
00:05:52.267 --> 00:05:54.633
If you only got dizzy
when you tidied up

93
00:05:54.633 --> 00:05:56.734
you should have
the clearest head
in the area.

94
00:06:22.734 --> 00:06:24.900
You're going to park
in the turning area?

95
00:06:24.900 --> 00:06:27.567
There's no room
in front of the house.
it blocks the road.

96
00:06:27.567 --> 00:06:30.368
However. I'm game
if you are. if you want
to block the road.

97
00:06:30.368 --> 00:06:33.001
It's just that I wish
you would consult me.

98
00:06:33.001 --> 00:06:35.500
I don't like you making
decisions unilaterally.

99
00:06:46.001 --> 00:06:49.267
Would you like me
to lock the car?

100
00:06:49.267 --> 00:06:52.267
I think so.
Don't you?

101
00:06:52.267 --> 00:06:55.167
We're practically
in Beirut.

102
00:06:59.101 --> 00:07:00.934
Onslow.

103
00:07:03.633 --> 00:07:05.867
Dicky.
Hyacinth.

104
00:07:07.267 --> 00:07:10.401
Why do you let him
call you "dicky"?

105
00:07:10.401 --> 00:07:13.567
How can I help it
if he calls me "dicky"?

106
00:07:23.134 --> 00:07:25.301
Queen mother's outside.

107
00:07:40.134 --> 00:07:42.167
Give US a hand. Rose.

108
00:07:42.167 --> 00:07:44.234
I'm expecting a call.

109
00:07:44.234 --> 00:07:47.468
I gave Boris this number.
The swine promised he'd ring.

110
00:08:00.434 --> 00:08:03.301
Leave--
leave it.

111
00:08:23.167 --> 00:08:25.934
- Richard!
- Now what?

112
00:08:25.934 --> 00:08:29.434
You shouldn't be
stretching your legs
like that at your age.

113
00:08:29.434 --> 00:08:31.567
It's not fitting
in broad daylight.

114
00:08:31.567 --> 00:08:33.567
in front
of prying eyes.

115
00:08:53.134 --> 00:08:55.800
Daisy:
Here we are then.

116
00:08:55.800 --> 00:08:57.800
Thanks. Daisy.

117
00:09:12.067 --> 00:09:14.767
Drink up.

118
00:09:14.767 --> 00:09:16.667
Tell me what's happened.

119
00:09:21.934 --> 00:09:24.533
Dad's not been--
well lately.

120
00:09:24.533 --> 00:09:27.900
Why wasn't I informed?

121
00:09:27.900 --> 00:09:30.967
It's not been
the kind of "not well"

122
00:09:30.967 --> 00:09:33.067
you'd want to be
informed about.

123
00:09:33.067 --> 00:09:35.067
What kind has it been?

124
00:09:40.201 --> 00:09:42.368
It's a bit embarrassing.

125
00:09:42.368 --> 00:09:44.533
Embarrassing?
Daddy?

126
00:09:44.533 --> 00:09:47.867
- He's a dirty old man.
- Shut up. onslow.

127
00:09:47.867 --> 00:09:51.034
Richard. go and keep
an eye on the car.

128
00:09:51.034 --> 00:09:54.633
I think I'll go
and keep an eye
on the car.

129
00:09:56.533 --> 00:09:58.301
What does onslow mean?

130
00:09:59.533 --> 00:10:01.301
He means...

131
00:10:01.301 --> 00:10:04.967
Dad's taken to going out
at night on his own lately.

132
00:10:04.967 --> 00:10:07.267
In the naughty.

133
00:10:10.967 --> 00:10:13.967
But--
but. but--

134
00:10:13.967 --> 00:10:16.034
why would father be
in the nude?

135
00:10:16.034 --> 00:10:17.834
He's in love
with the milkwoman.

136
00:10:17.834 --> 00:10:19.900
Don't be so ridiculous.

137
00:10:19.900 --> 00:10:22.900
You'd have thought so if you'd
seen him peddling after her

138
00:10:22.900 --> 00:10:26.401
stark naked on his bike.

139
00:10:26.401 --> 00:10:29.034
He chased her for a mile.
down by the canal.

140
00:10:29.034 --> 00:10:31.900
But the milkwoman doesn't go
anywhere near the canal.
does she?

141
00:10:31.900 --> 00:10:34.101
She did last night.

142
00:10:34.101 --> 00:10:35.900
He caught her
on her way to bingo.

143
00:10:35.900 --> 00:10:38.434
Well...

144
00:10:38.434 --> 00:10:40.700
You know how fond he is
of dairy products.

145
00:10:40.700 --> 00:10:43.134
I expect he wanted
to order extra cream.

146
00:11:03.101 --> 00:11:06.101
Why would your father
have been naked?

147
00:11:06.101 --> 00:11:07.533
I don't believe it.

148
00:11:07.533 --> 00:11:09.500
And keep your voice down.

149
00:11:09.500 --> 00:11:13.134
It's bad enough
with his clothes on.

150
00:11:13.134 --> 00:11:15.700
Daddy would never
be naked.

151
00:11:15.700 --> 00:11:18.167
Why would daddy be naked
when he's got his name down

152
00:11:18.167 --> 00:11:20.600
for a nice
old person's bungalow?

153
00:11:26.800 --> 00:11:28.533
<i>This way. Mrs. Bucket.

154
00:11:28.533 --> 00:11:30.667
It's "bouquet."

155
00:11:33.967 --> 00:11:35.567
How are you feeling
Mr. Oxley?

156
00:11:35.567 --> 00:11:37.700
Better than him.

157
00:11:39.067 --> 00:11:40.767
Daddy.

158
00:11:40.767 --> 00:11:43.834
I'm afraid he won't be aware
of very much. Mrs. Bucket--

159
00:11:43.834 --> 00:11:45.600
"bouquet."

160
00:11:45.600 --> 00:11:48.167
He's quite comfortable
but heavily sedated.

161
00:11:48.167 --> 00:11:50.834
Oh. daddy.

162
00:11:50.834 --> 00:11:54.667
Should he be in a ward
with a person who wears
his hat in bed?

163
00:11:55.934 --> 00:11:57.533
I'll leave you
with your father.

164
00:11:57.533 --> 00:11:59.067
Doctor...

165
00:11:59.067 --> 00:12:01.567
What condition was my father
in when he was admitted?

166
00:12:01.567 --> 00:12:02.867
Drunk as a skunk.

167
00:12:06.434 --> 00:12:10.600
I expect he was flushed
from excessive cycling.

168
00:12:10.600 --> 00:12:13.167
Can you describe
what he was wearing.
doctor?

169
00:12:13.167 --> 00:12:14.967
Very quickly.

170
00:12:14.967 --> 00:12:16.633
Very little. really.

171
00:12:16.633 --> 00:12:19.434
To be honest...
Nothing at all.

172
00:12:19.434 --> 00:12:21.667
There must be
some mistake.

173
00:12:21.667 --> 00:12:24.500
That's what I thought.
It was quite
a chilly evening.

174
00:12:26.201 --> 00:12:27.900
He'd been in the canal.

175
00:12:27.900 --> 00:12:31.767
He was that plastered.
he wobbled off into the canal.

176
00:12:31.767 --> 00:12:34.001
That explains it.

177
00:12:34.001 --> 00:12:36.734
My father was cycling
along the canal

178
00:12:36.734 --> 00:12:38.800
when he saw
someone in distress.

179
00:12:38.800 --> 00:12:40.700
so he removed
his outer garments

180
00:12:40.700 --> 00:12:44.401
and dived in to save them.
Oh. brave daddy.

181
00:12:44.401 --> 00:12:47.734
Very commendable.

182
00:12:47.734 --> 00:12:51.101
He must've removed more
than his outer garments.
Mrs. Bucket.

183
00:12:51.101 --> 00:12:53.967
"Bouquet."

184
00:12:53.967 --> 00:12:57.067
When he was pulled out
he was absolutely naked.

185
00:12:57.067 --> 00:12:59.368
Pollution.

186
00:12:59.368 --> 00:13:03.800
What he'd been wearing was
obviously dissolved
by the pollution.

187
00:13:03.800 --> 00:13:06.468
If you'll excuse me.
I must attend to my
other patients.

188
00:13:06.468 --> 00:13:09.533
Why is he sedated
after such a plucky act?

189
00:13:09.533 --> 00:13:12.401
He was highly excited.
and then of course
there was the injury.

190
00:13:12.401 --> 00:13:15.001
From the milk bottle?
Poor lamb.

191
00:13:15.001 --> 00:13:17.867
Where is the injury?
You may tell me the worst.

192
00:13:17.867 --> 00:13:21.101
- Uh. Mrs.--
- I demand to be shown

193
00:13:21.101 --> 00:13:23.067
the extent
of his injuries.

194
00:13:24.500 --> 00:13:26.134
Very well.

195
00:13:39.900 --> 00:13:41.767
Where is the injury?

196
00:13:41.767 --> 00:13:44.001
Never you mind.

197
00:14:02.667 --> 00:14:04.967
How are things?

198
00:14:04.967 --> 00:14:08.834
I'm too distressed
at the moment. Elizabeth.

199
00:14:08.834 --> 00:14:11.167
My father is recovering
from injuries sustained

200
00:14:11.167 --> 00:14:13.334
in the course
of a very plucky action...

201
00:14:13.334 --> 00:14:16.034
Which he modestly
forbids me to discuss.

202
00:14:16.034 --> 00:14:18.834
Oh. well. is there
anything i--

203
00:14:18.834 --> 00:14:21.434
just give me time
to recover my composure.

204
00:14:21.434 --> 00:14:24.368
and then come and take tea
with me at 3:25.

205
00:14:25.500 --> 00:14:29.034
3:25?
Not 27?

206
00:14:41.567 --> 00:14:43.567
Oh. it's you. Elizabeth!

207
00:14:43.567 --> 00:14:46.201
A tiny bit early. perhaps.
but do come in.

208
00:14:47.500 --> 00:14:49.734
I thought it was 3:25.

209
00:14:49.734 --> 00:14:52.834
- Not quite. dear.
- My watch says 3:25.

210
00:14:52.834 --> 00:14:56.267
Oh. that watch. yes.
I expect it would.

211
00:14:56.267 --> 00:14:59.101
Shall we go through
to the kitchen?

212
00:14:59.101 --> 00:15:02.434
I don't know why you won't
let me through your back door.

213
00:15:02.434 --> 00:15:06.101
I think it's so common.
don't you. using back doors?

214
00:15:06.101 --> 00:15:09.267
No. the proper way
for my guests.
I always feel.

215
00:15:09.267 --> 00:15:10.800
is through
the front door.

216
00:15:10.800 --> 00:15:13.334
And then straight
into the kitchen?

217
00:15:13.334 --> 00:15:14.667
Well. yes.

218
00:15:14.667 --> 00:15:16.867
Unless. of course.
it's someone special.

219
00:15:17.967 --> 00:15:20.067
Now I know you're saying
to yourself.

220
00:15:20.067 --> 00:15:22.167
"how is she
being so brave?"

221
00:15:22.167 --> 00:15:23.834
Well. yes. I am brave.

222
00:15:23.834 --> 00:15:25.600
My father would wish it.

223
00:15:25.600 --> 00:15:29.167
I admit I miss my Sheridan
at times like these.

224
00:15:29.167 --> 00:15:32.234
He's such a comfort to his
mother as well as being
terribly gifted.

225
00:15:32.234 --> 00:15:34.667
Do sit down. Elizabeth.
Make yourself at home.

226
00:15:34.667 --> 00:15:36.867
Oh. not there. dear.
I like to face the window.

227
00:15:45.834 --> 00:15:47.368
Lemon?

228
00:15:47.368 --> 00:15:48.468
W--

229
00:15:50.067 --> 00:15:52.067
my word.

230
00:15:52.067 --> 00:15:55.067
doesn't someone look smarter
than she did earlier?

231
00:15:55.067 --> 00:15:57.167
Something new. dear?

232
00:15:57.167 --> 00:15:59.201
No. no.
I've had it ages.

233
00:15:59.201 --> 00:16:01.234
Oh. yes.
I can see you have now.

234
00:16:03.067 --> 00:16:06.067
I thought we'd have
the nicer China.

235
00:16:06.067 --> 00:16:07.734
Oh. thank you.
Hyacinth.

236
00:16:07.734 --> 00:16:10.234
They're something
of a family heirloom.

237
00:16:10.234 --> 00:16:12.368
Oh. god. don't give me
anything special.

238
00:16:12.368 --> 00:16:14.401
You will be careful.
won't you. dear?

239
00:16:16.500 --> 00:16:18.034
Biscuit?

240
00:16:18.034 --> 00:16:20.434
Thank you. Hyacinth.

241
00:16:22.900 --> 00:16:25.734
I used to have six of these
until one fell into the hands

242
00:16:25.734 --> 00:16:27.900
of my brother-in-law onslow
one Christmas.

243
00:16:27.900 --> 00:16:29.267
I could've killed him.

244
00:16:29.267 --> 00:16:32.667
Of course. one can't make
a fuss on festive occasions.

245
00:16:32.667 --> 00:16:35.734
but he certainly got
the short end of the Turkey.
I can tell you.

246
00:16:38.101 --> 00:16:40.700
Did they tell you what
was wrong with your father?

247
00:16:42.101 --> 00:16:44.167
Something mildly
embarrassing.

248
00:16:44.167 --> 00:16:47.167
One of those minor
geriatric complaints.

249
00:16:47.167 --> 00:16:49.468
I couldn't catch
the medical terminology.

250
00:16:49.468 --> 00:16:50.934
Oh.

251
00:16:50.934 --> 00:16:52.468
<i>Aaah!

252
00:16:58.034 --> 00:17:00.867
No. you cannot have
a number 24.

253
00:17:00.867 --> 00:17:02.734
nor a double portion
of 37.

254
00:17:02.734 --> 00:17:05.700
This isn't
the Chinese take-away.

255
00:17:05.700 --> 00:17:09.267
This is a private
slimline white telephone

256
00:17:09.267 --> 00:17:11.401
with no connection
whatsoever

257
00:17:11.401 --> 00:17:13.468
to any business or trade--

258
00:17:13.468 --> 00:17:15.900
especially not one
of foreign extraction.

259
00:17:18.867 --> 00:17:21.001
Oh. Hyacinth.
I'm so sorry.

260
00:17:21.001 --> 00:17:22.867
Now do stop
worrying. dear.

261
00:17:22.867 --> 00:17:25.900
We're not going to fall out
over a cup and saucer.

262
00:17:25.900 --> 00:17:29.167
even a very old.
irreplacable cup and saucer.

263
00:17:29.167 --> 00:17:31.368
Oh. it would
happen to me.

264
00:17:31.368 --> 00:17:33.401
Believe me.
I do understand.

265
00:17:33.401 --> 00:17:35.900
It can't be easy to be dainty
when you're all thumbs.

266
00:17:37.967 --> 00:17:39.334
There. I think
that will do

267
00:17:39.334 --> 00:17:41.201
until I can afford
a little more time.

268
00:17:41.201 --> 00:17:43.734
- Oh. dear.
- We're not going
to worry anymore

269
00:17:43.734 --> 00:17:45.500
about a bit
of expensive carpet

270
00:17:45.500 --> 00:17:47.667
and a cup that's
been around for ages.

271
00:17:47.667 --> 00:17:50.967
Which reminds me.
did you soil
your dress. dear?

272
00:17:50.967 --> 00:17:52.267
Oh. no!
No. no.

273
00:17:52.267 --> 00:17:54.134
No. surprising it didn't.
I'm fine.

274
00:17:54.134 --> 00:17:55.900
That's amazing.

275
00:17:55.900 --> 00:17:59.167
- Would you like another
cup of Earl grey?
- No! Thank you.

276
00:17:59.167 --> 00:18:01.767
- In a beaker. perhaps?
- No. nothing. Thank you. no.

277
00:18:01.767 --> 00:18:04.101
Well. it's all over now.

278
00:18:04.101 --> 00:18:06.567
All over everywhere.

279
00:18:06.567 --> 00:18:08.368
Do sit down again.
Elizabeth.

280
00:18:11.267 --> 00:18:14.001
Have you heard
from Gail recently?

281
00:18:14.001 --> 00:18:16.834
Yes. she rang
at the weekend.

282
00:18:16.834 --> 00:18:19.001
That's nice.
I think a daughter
always should.

283
00:18:19.001 --> 00:18:21.267
Gail's very good
that way.

284
00:18:21.267 --> 00:18:23.401
So's my Sheridan.

285
00:18:23.401 --> 00:18:26.001
I tremble to think
sometimes

286
00:18:26.001 --> 00:18:28.368
what he spends
on phone calls
to his mother.

287
00:18:28.368 --> 00:18:30.368
Not that he can't
afford it. of course.

288
00:18:30.368 --> 00:18:33.034
They gave him a very good
Grant at the poly. you know.

289
00:18:33.034 --> 00:18:35.967
to stop him being tempted
by Oxford or Cambridge.

290
00:18:37.967 --> 00:18:40.001
Gail's studying hard.

291
00:18:40.001 --> 00:18:42.234
Well. it's a struggle.
isn't it.

292
00:18:42.234 --> 00:18:44.500
when they're not
academically gifted?

293
00:18:45.734 --> 00:18:48.034
Our Gail is
academically gifted.

294
00:18:48.034 --> 00:18:49.633
Is she?

295
00:18:49.633 --> 00:18:52.434
Oh. wonder who I can be
confusing her with?

296
00:18:52.434 --> 00:18:54.867
Perhaps it's that boy
she's living so openly

297
00:18:54.867 --> 00:18:57.001
and unashamedly
unmarried with.

298
00:18:58.101 --> 00:18:59.967
I hardly think so.

299
00:18:59.967 --> 00:19:02.533
Harold is a very nice boy
with a first-class brain.

300
00:19:02.533 --> 00:19:06.301
- Is he?
- Yes. he is. Hyacinth.
I can assure you.

301
00:19:06.301 --> 00:19:08.834
You'd never know
to look at him. would you?

302
00:19:11.633 --> 00:19:14.667
I hope that's not daddy
going septic.

303
00:19:20.301 --> 00:19:23.667
The "bouquet" residence.
the lady of the house
speaking.

304
00:19:24.667 --> 00:19:26.500
Oh. it's you. Violet.

305
00:19:26.500 --> 00:19:28.301
It's my sister. Violet.

306
00:19:28.301 --> 00:19:30.267
The one who married
the turf-accountant.

307
00:19:30.267 --> 00:19:33.167
He built that big house
with room for a sauna
and a pony.

308
00:19:33.167 --> 00:19:34.800
You've heard me speak
about Violet.

309
00:19:34.800 --> 00:19:36.334
Frequently.

310
00:19:37.867 --> 00:19:41.434
Slow down. Violet. dear.
You sound very excited.

311
00:19:41.434 --> 00:19:43.533
I know it's been
a shock about daddy.

312
00:19:44.900 --> 00:19:47.867
What are you
excited about?

313
00:19:47.867 --> 00:19:50.034
Violet. that's not a word
I ever expected

314
00:19:50.034 --> 00:19:51.867
to hear you use
on a telephone.

315
00:19:53.201 --> 00:19:54.401
<i>Bruce?

316
00:19:54.401 --> 00:19:56.368
What about Bruce?

317
00:19:58.034 --> 00:19:59.900
I Don--

318
00:19:59.900 --> 00:20:01.834
oh. d--

319
00:20:01.834 --> 00:20:04.301
well. I've never liked him
wholeheartedly

320
00:20:04.301 --> 00:20:06.267
on account of those
ice cubes he serves

321
00:20:06.267 --> 00:20:07.734
in the shape
of naked ladies.

322
00:20:09.500 --> 00:20:11.101
Why shouldn't he
buy a whip?

323
00:20:11.101 --> 00:20:13.800
I expect he got it
from a jockey.

324
00:20:13.800 --> 00:20:16.134
What does he use it for?

325
00:20:18.267 --> 00:20:19.800
Violet.

326
00:20:19.800 --> 00:20:22.500
would you ring back. dear?

327
00:20:22.500 --> 00:20:24.234
No. no.
All right. all right.

328
00:20:24.234 --> 00:20:25.834
I'll stay on the phone.

329
00:20:25.834 --> 00:20:27.734
<i>Hold on.

330
00:20:27.734 --> 00:20:29.368
There's a person
at the front door.

331
00:20:29.368 --> 00:20:32.734
Elizabeth. would you see
to that for me. dear?

332
00:20:32.734 --> 00:20:35.368
Kindly inform whoever it is
that I am at home

333
00:20:35.368 --> 00:20:37.500
and that I will
receive them momentarily.

334
00:20:40.500 --> 00:20:44.434
No. dear. it's Elizabeth
from next door.

335
00:20:44.434 --> 00:20:46.600
That's right.
the one who's all thumbs.

336
00:20:49.834 --> 00:20:53.468
You met her once at one
of my candlelight suppers.

337
00:20:53.468 --> 00:20:55.867
What do you mean
you couldn't see anybody?

338
00:20:57.934 --> 00:20:59.500
Oh. yes.
she's fine.

339
00:20:59.500 --> 00:21:01.800
She's just broken
one of grandmother's cups.

340
00:21:03.700 --> 00:21:07.067
It's a security latch.
There's a little button.

341
00:21:07.067 --> 00:21:08.967
Richard had it installed...

342
00:21:08.967 --> 00:21:10.734
To protect me
from anyone desperate.

343
00:21:12.533 --> 00:21:14.800
They would have to be.

344
00:21:17.368 --> 00:21:18.867
Ah. electric.

345
00:21:18.867 --> 00:21:21.667
- Have you been next door?
- Yes. there's nobody in.

346
00:21:21.667 --> 00:21:23.101
I know. I'm here.

347
00:21:23.101 --> 00:21:25.533
- I've left you a card.
- Oh.

348
00:21:25.533 --> 00:21:28.034
It's the electric man
to read your meter.

349
00:21:28.034 --> 00:21:30.734
Is it the one
with the funny mustache?

350
00:21:32.667 --> 00:21:34.533
Tell her yes.

351
00:21:34.533 --> 00:21:36.034
He says yes.

352
00:21:36.034 --> 00:21:38.667
Make him wait there
till I've looked at his feet.

353
00:21:40.600 --> 00:21:43.067
Violet.
I have to go. dear.

354
00:21:43.067 --> 00:21:44.567
I've got the electric.

355
00:21:47.834 --> 00:21:49.034
Oh my goodness.

356
00:21:49.034 --> 00:21:51.167
I'm so sorry.

357
00:21:51.167 --> 00:21:52.900
I've been thinking
about my sister.

358
00:21:52.900 --> 00:21:55.101
She seems to have had
a rather active holiday.

359
00:21:55.101 --> 00:21:57.533
Oh. the shoes.

360
00:21:57.533 --> 00:22:00.633
You remembered
our procedure
from last time.

361
00:22:00.633 --> 00:22:03.267
Very well.

362
00:22:03.267 --> 00:22:06.134
Leave them outside
and do come in.

363
00:22:06.134 --> 00:22:07.834
Thank you. dear.

364
00:22:09.034 --> 00:22:11.567
You're a great improvement
on the one I had before.

365
00:22:11.567 --> 00:22:14.533
He used to brush
against my walls.

366
00:22:14.533 --> 00:22:17.034
Of course I rang
his superiors.

367
00:22:17.034 --> 00:22:20.667
I said I will not have
electric men brushing
against my walls.

368
00:22:22.434 --> 00:22:24.934
Elizabeth.
close the door. dear.
The heat's on.

369
00:22:26.834 --> 00:22:28.334
- Ah!
- Oh!

370
00:22:28.334 --> 00:22:29.934
Fingers.

371
00:22:32.800 --> 00:22:35.334
8321.

372
00:22:39.201 --> 00:22:41.001
Correct.

373
00:22:47.767 --> 00:22:50.401
Is your electric
as clean as it was.
do you think?

374
00:22:50.401 --> 00:22:53.368
My hops?? Are sometimes
very difficult to clean.

375
00:22:53.368 --> 00:22:54.967
Cleanest fuel
there is.

376
00:22:54.967 --> 00:22:56.834
It goes to some
very funny families.

377
00:22:56.834 --> 00:22:59.800
Would you have mine checked
to make quite sure
I get it first?

378
00:22:59.800 --> 00:23:01.700
Leave it with me. lady.

379
00:23:01.700 --> 00:23:05.500
Because I won't have it
if it's already been to some
of those other places.

380
00:23:05.500 --> 00:23:07.368
Right-o. madam.

381
00:23:07.368 --> 00:23:08.900
Much obliged.

382
00:23:14.468 --> 00:23:16.267
It's only me.

383
00:23:23.167 --> 00:23:25.201
Shouldn't that be.
"it's only I." dear?

384
00:23:25.201 --> 00:23:28.468
Especially when
you're shouting it where
the neighbors can hear.

385
00:23:28.468 --> 00:23:30.234
I'm not sure.

386
00:23:30.234 --> 00:23:32.633
Neither am I.
so you must be careful.

387
00:23:32.633 --> 00:23:34.567
How's your father?

388
00:23:34.567 --> 00:23:37.001
I rang.
the ward sister
answered.

389
00:23:37.001 --> 00:23:39.834
She says he's sitting up
and beginning to take
an interest...

390
00:23:39.834 --> 00:23:42.800
- That's good.
- ...In the physiotherapist.

391
00:23:44.633 --> 00:23:48.134
He thinks he's in love
with the physiotherapist.

392
00:23:48.134 --> 00:23:50.201
It's probably
just the drugs.

393
00:23:50.201 --> 00:23:54.567
And that swine Bruce
wants my sister to wear
some awful leather outfit.

394
00:23:54.567 --> 00:23:58.001
Oh. is he going
to take her motorcycling?

395
00:23:58.001 --> 00:24:00.234
No. it's not motorcycling.

396
00:24:00.234 --> 00:24:02.434
It's something
he picked up in Spain.

397
00:24:02.434 --> 00:24:04.434
What. bullfighting?

398
00:24:04.434 --> 00:24:06.700
No. I don't think
it's that either.

399
00:24:06.700 --> 00:24:08.734
Anyway. dear.
enough of my problems.

400
00:24:08.734 --> 00:24:11.834
- Did you manage
to get the parsley?
- Yes. in the kitchen.

401
00:24:11.834 --> 00:24:14.468
- You'll never guess
who I bumped into.
- Good.

402
00:24:14.468 --> 00:24:16.834
Would you Polish
those glasses for me. dear.

403
00:24:16.834 --> 00:24:20.067
and then give me a hand
with buffing up the cruet?

404
00:24:24.633 --> 00:24:27.034
Sheridan.

405
00:24:27.034 --> 00:24:30.368
How sensitive of you
to call. dear.

406
00:24:30.368 --> 00:24:33.301
What a close psychic link
we have. you and I.

407
00:24:33.301 --> 00:24:34.900
What does he want?

408
00:24:34.900 --> 00:24:36.600
<i>Wantsanything.

409
00:24:36.600 --> 00:24:38.834
He's just ringing
his mother.

410
00:24:38.834 --> 00:24:41.134
You need how much.
Sheridan?

411
00:24:42.134 --> 00:24:43.667
For what?

412
00:24:43.667 --> 00:24:45.700
You've joined
an organization.

413
00:24:45.700 --> 00:24:47.834
That's nice. dear.
making friends.

414
00:24:47.834 --> 00:24:49.834
What kind
of an organization?

415
00:24:49.834 --> 00:24:51.834
Is it like a club.
a golf club?

416
00:24:53.001 --> 00:24:55.867
Not a golf club. I see.
Just a group of friends.

417
00:24:57.633 --> 00:24:59.667
You call yourselves
what. dear?

418
00:24:59.667 --> 00:25:03.734
"The sword of the people"?
Do be careful. Sheridan.

419
00:25:03.734 --> 00:25:06.267
Make sure they're not
too sharp.

420
00:25:07.267 --> 00:25:09.800
Always wear a mask.

421
00:25:09.800 --> 00:25:12.934
You do wear masks?
Oh. that's very sensible.

422
00:25:14.667 --> 00:25:17.834
You'll pay
daddy back when?

423
00:25:17.834 --> 00:25:20.301
When you've robbed
your first bank? Sheridan!

424
00:25:20.301 --> 00:25:22.267
Look. dear.

425
00:25:22.267 --> 00:25:25.434
couldn't you find some nice
philatelic society to join?

426
00:25:28.067 --> 00:25:30.334
No. we will not
send a check.

427
00:25:30.334 --> 00:25:32.900
Richard. that's Sheridan
on the phone--

428
00:25:32.900 --> 00:25:34.967
<i>ohh.

429
00:25:36.934 --> 00:25:39.567
Now listen. Sheridan.
you've upset your father.

430
00:25:39.567 --> 00:25:42.900
Oh. major. I'm so sorry.

431
00:25:42.900 --> 00:25:46.067
I was expecting
another call.

432
00:25:46.067 --> 00:25:47.633
Yes.

433
00:25:47.633 --> 00:25:50.401
Oh. yes.
my candlelight supper
is still on.

434
00:25:50.401 --> 00:25:54.633
Oh. it's been a funny day.
but we have to press on.

435
00:25:54.633 --> 00:25:57.934
Would I like some flowers
from your conservatory?

436
00:25:57.934 --> 00:25:59.434
How very kind.

437
00:25:59.434 --> 00:26:01.600
Yes. I'll pop along now.

438
00:26:02.934 --> 00:26:06.001
That's very civilized
of you. major. Bye.

439
00:26:06.001 --> 00:26:07.900
What about Sheridan?

440
00:26:07.900 --> 00:26:09.434
Don't send him
any money.

441
00:26:36.034 --> 00:26:38.567
Oh. isn't this delightful?

442
00:26:38.567 --> 00:26:42.034
This is so kind of you.

443
00:26:42.034 --> 00:26:44.700
I've cut some
prime blooms for you.

444
00:26:44.700 --> 00:26:46.301
Oh. lovely.

445
00:26:47.567 --> 00:26:50.201
Oh. you grew them
all yourself.

446
00:26:50.201 --> 00:26:52.434
Especially for you.

447
00:26:52.434 --> 00:26:54.101
Oh...

448
00:26:55.434 --> 00:26:58.368
I must rush.
I've left the oven on.

449
00:27:05.001 --> 00:27:07.500
Hyacinth:
I didn't know
you were so athletic.

450
00:27:08.500 --> 00:27:10.167
- Aaah. Ooh.
- Ooh!

451
00:27:33.600 --> 00:27:35.767
What's wrong now?

452
00:27:35.767 --> 00:27:38.001
Nothing is wrong.

453
00:27:38.001 --> 00:27:41.667
As far as anyone is concerned.
nothing is wrong.

454
00:27:41.667 --> 00:27:44.301
We're going to have
a candlelight supper.

455
00:27:44.301 --> 00:27:46.500
It's going to be
the usual success.

456
00:27:47.767 --> 00:27:49.434
I see no reason

457
00:27:49.434 --> 00:27:52.700
for trailing our problems
in front of our friends.

458
00:27:52.700 --> 00:27:54.301
Is the major coming?

459
00:27:54.301 --> 00:27:56.900
Yes. Richard.

460
00:27:56.900 --> 00:28:01.767
I do believe the major
will be coming.

461
00:28:01.767 --> 00:28:03.867
And it's a good job
he is a major.

462
00:28:03.867 --> 00:28:07.633
If he was a sergeant
he wouldn't get a foot
past the door.
